<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900417-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>900417-0022.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>04/17/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   LITHUANIA CALLED for talks with Gorbachev about Moscow'seconomic threats.   Amid reports that the Baltic republic was prepared tocompromise on certain independence-related issues, Lithuaniaappealed in a telegram for a meeting with the Soviet leaderto discuss details of the Kremlin's threatened economicsanctions. The move followed a meeting of the republic'sleadership. Gorbachev, in an ultimatum issued Friday, gaveLithuania 48 hours to end its secession bid or face a cutoffof crucial products. Moscow apparently hasn't taken anyaction.</LP><TEXT>   Vilnius Radio reported that &quot;political decisions&quot; aboutGorbachev's ultimatum would be addressed during a meetingtoday of Lithuania's parliament.   ---   NEPAL'S KING ASKED the once-banned opposition to form aninterim government.   Bowing to demands for further democratic change, KingBirendra asked the Nepali Congress Party to form a governmentto rule until the country's first free elections in nearlythree decades are held. The opposition party and theseven-party United Left Front led nationwide pro-democracyprotests that began in February. The move came after themonarch dissolved the nonpartisan national assembly andannounced the resignation of the prime minister.   The concessions followed the king's April 8 decision tolift a 29-year-old ban on political parties in an effort toend the protests in the Himalayan nation.   ---   The Supreme Court refused to hear the appeal of DaltonPrejean, a retarded man scheduled to be executed in Louisianalast November for the shooting death of a state trooper.Prejean alleged, among other things, that his rights had beenviolated because he is black but was convicted by a jury fromwhich blacks were excluded.   ---   A leaking gas cylinder exploded aboard a moving commutertrain in northeastern India, killing at least 80 people andinjuring 65 others, authorities said. The number ofpassengers wasn't known, and the casualty toll is expected torise. Fire swept through the 16-car train as it traveled inBihar state, about 500 miles southeast of New Delhi.                                                                                                          India's government banned eight militant Moslem groups inKashmir and closed two newspapers in its latest effort tocontrol unrest in the disputed territory. At least 270 peoplehave been killed in a three-month-old independence drive inthe region.   ---   Nicaragua's Ortega raised the possibility that the April25 inauguration of President-elect Violeta Chamorro could bepostponed if the Contra rebels aren't disarmed by that date.In Washington, Bush suggested that a congressional delay on aNicaraguan aid package would be an affront to Chamorro.   ---   Election returns in Yugoslavia showed that a center-rightcoalition won a legislative majority in Slovenia's April 8multiparty balloting. The final results will allow thesix-party alliance in the northern republic to form thenation's first non-Communist regional government in 45 years.   ---   Delegates from 17 nations gathered for a WhiteHouse-backed parley today on global warming, amid criticismthat Bush isn't dealing with the problem. At the two-daymeeting, the U.S. is expected to urge increased internationalresearch on the greenhouse effect and its economicimplications.   ---   The U.S. and Soviet Union were urged in a National Academyof Sciences report to follow a coordinated but independentexploration of Mars with robots. The study's head said heenvisioned a $10 billion project in which the U.S. launchedthree robotic &quot;excursions&quot; to Mars as early as the year 2000.   ---   Mandela attended a rock concert at London's WembleyStadium and, in an address to the crowd of about 72,000people, the 71-year-old black nationalist leader urged theworld to maintain anti-apartheid sanctions against SouthAfrica. Prime Minister Thatcher already has eased such curbs.   ---   Lawyers in Cincinnati entered innocent pleas for thecity's Contemporary Arts Center and its director onmisdemeanor charges alleging that photographs in an exhibitof the works of the late Robert Mapplethorpe are obscene.Some of the photos are of nude children and homosexual acts.A pretrial hearing was scheduled for April 30.   ---   Gelindo Bordin of Italy won the 94th Boston Marathon. TheOlympic champion's finishing time was 2:08:19. Rosa Mota ofPortugal, also a reigning Olympic titlist, won the women'sdivision in a time of 2:25:24.</TEXT></DOC>